d Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Atherton,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place near Manchester named Atherton, from the Old English personal name <i>Æthelhere</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’.","English: habitational name from Hatherton, Staffordshire, from Old English <i>haguthorn</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘the hill where hawthorn grows’.","English (East Anglia): topographic name from Middle English <i>at ther doune</i> ‘(dweller) on the hill’ (Old English <i>æt thǣre dūne</i>). Through confusion of <i>-don</i> and <i>-ton</i>, <i>Attherdoune</i> was altered to <i>Atherton</i>, <i>Adderton</i>, and <i>Atterton</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"born","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Heinz, Helmut, Berthold, Frieda, Friedrich, Fritz, Gerhard, Horst, Jutta.","English: variant of   Bourne  .","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>borgne</i> ‘one-eyed, squint-eyed’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourne","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from southern Middle English <i>bourne</i>, Old English <i>burna</i>, <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Bourn in Cambridgeshire or Bourne in Lincolnshire. In surnames the reference is often to an old stream called <i>burna</i>, surviving as the name of a farm. This word was replaced as the general word for a stream in southern dialects by Old English <i>brōc</i> (see   Brook  ) and came to be restricted in meaning to a stream flowing only intermittently, especially in winter."]},{"name":"Borner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerd, Hans, Irmgard.","North German (also <b>Börner</b>): variant of   Born  , + the suffix <i>-er</i> denoting an inhabitant.","North German: occupational name for a stockman, from Middle Low German <i>bornen</i> ‘to water (farm animals)’."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"AinTree","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Daventry (Northants), locally pronounced  <i>Daintree</i> and  <i>Dauntry</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Daintry","meanings":["English:  See  Daintree  ."]},{"name":"Daventry","meanings":["English:  See  Daintree  ."]},{"name":"Danter","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Daintree  .  Compare  Dainter  ."]},{"name":"Daintrey","meanings":["English:  See  Daintree  ."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":16,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":41,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Emma De Atherton, born de AinTree was born about 1274, in Mobberley, Cheshire, England. She married Henry de Atherton about 1295, in Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1319, in Atherton, Lancashire, England, at the age of 46."},"et":{"about 1274–1319":"umbes 1274–1319","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1325–1396":"1325–1396","1274–1319":"1274–1319","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","circa 1295":"umbes 1295","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","about 1387":"umbes 1387","1319":"1319","1280":"1280","about 1274":"umbes 1274","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Malling, Kent, England":"Atherton, Lancashire, England","Hindley, Chorley, Lancashire, England":"Mobberley, Cheshire, England","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1274–1319":"noin 1274–1319","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1325–1396":"1325–1396","1274–1319":"1274–1319","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","circa 1295":"noin 1295","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","about 1387":"noin 1387","1319":"1319","1280":"1280","a